      <hedline>
        <hl1>In Service of the Music?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Mark Kross letter about Jan 7 article on jazz education</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Jazz Is Alive and Well. In the Classroom, Anyway.'' by Nate Chinen [Jan. 7]:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Jazz Is Alive and Well. In the Classroom, Anyway.'' by Nate Chinen [Jan. 7]:</p>
        <p>One of the positive consequences of -- and perhaps contributing factor toward -- the significant expansion of the jazz education industry in the past 20 years is that it has allowed musicians to maintain a career in jazz, especially as the number of playing gigs fades and the pay for many of those gigs remains the same. As a 50-year-old jazz musician and educator, I have benefited from this expansion, but I do wonder if at some point the jazz education industry will exist more to perpetuate the industry itself than the music.</p>
        <p>Mark Kross  Concord, Mass.</p>
        <p>JAZZ EDUCATION</p>
      </block>
